column6: The prefix "2" indicates engines built by Packard, otherwise as Merlin 66, optimised for low-altitude operation.

A "low altitude" version of Merlin with cropped supercharger impellers for increased power at lower altitudes, as per the Merlin XXX; fitted with a Coffman engine starter; used mainly in Fleet Air Arm aircraft. First production Merlin 32 delivered 17 June 1942.

A variant of the Merlin XX fitted with single-stage, single-speed supercharger for low altitude Spitfire use. First production Merlin 45 delivered 13 January 1941.  First of specialised engines for Spitfire Mk V variants and early Seafires.
Version of Merlin 45 with "cropped" (smaller diameter) supercharger impeller allowing greater boost at low altitudes.
Adapted with a Marshall compressor (often called a "blower") to pressurise the cockpit. First production Merlin 47 delivered 2 December 1941.
Low-altitude version with supercharger impeller "cropped" to 9.5 in (241 mm) in diameter.11 Merlin 50 series was first to use the Bendix Stromberg "negative-g" carburettor.111
First variant fitted with two-stage, two-speed supercharger; rated for high altitude.

Production variant of Merlin 60 fitted with a new two-speed two-stage supercharger providing increased power at medium to high altitudes.2 First British production variant to incorporate two-piece cylinder blocks designed by Rolls-Royce for the Packard Merlin. First production Merlin 61 delivered 2 March 1942.
Fitted with supercharger rated for low altitude; Bendix-Stromberg anti-g carburettor 122
Same as Merlin 76 with a pressurising blower 1
Development of Merlin B; Crankcase and cylinder blocks became three separate castings with bolt-on cylinder heads. First flight in Hawker Horsley 21 December 1935.

column5: 1,030 hp (768 kW) at 3,000 rpm at 5,500 ft (1,676 m) with + 6 psi (41 kPa) boost
column6: Used 100% glycol coolant. First production Merlin II delivered 10 August 1937.1

column5: 1,310 hp (977 kW) at 3,000 rpm at 9,000 ft (2,743 m) with 100 octane fuel and +12 psi (83 kPa) boost (5-minute limit).
column6: Variant of Merlin II with universal propeller shaft, able to be fitted with de Havilland or Rotol propellers. From late 1939, using 100 octane fuel and + 12 psi (83 kPa) boost, the Merlin III developed 1,310 hp (977 kW) at 3,000 rpm at 9,000 ft (2,700 m). Later developing 1,440 hp (1,074 kW) at 3,000 rpm, +16 psi (110 kPa) boost at 5,500 ft (1,676 m) for the Sea Hurricane. Using 87 Octane fuel the power ratings were the same as the Merlin II. First production Merlin III delivered 1 July 1938.

Coffman cartridge starter. First version of Merlin to use 30/70% glycol/water coolant with reinforced construction, able to use constant boost pressure of up to +12 psi (83 kPa) using 100 octane fuel. First production Merlin XII, 2 September 1939.1

column5: 1,490 hp (1,111 kW) at 3,000 rpm, +16 psi (110 kPa) boost, with 100 Octane fuel at 12,500 ft (3,810 m).
column6: First production version with two speed supercharger giving boost pressures of up to + 14 psi (97 kPa).1 First production Merlin XX, 4 July 1940.nb
